The Trojan horse of Europe
Berkeley – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be allocated.
Conditions will have to be attached.
The Greek government will make its usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be problems to come.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was to have allowed Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already evident, however, that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite a lack of productivity.
But this answer is too simplistic, in that such signs of malfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if it's not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy do a little better.
These countries, like Greece, must also face strong budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to ask for help.
All this poses just one question: was the true error not to have created the euro?
Inasmuch as I was one of the rare Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you would be right to ask: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My response is no, the creation of the euro was not a mistake, but it may well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the road to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis may well make this one look like a stroll in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency funding mechanism.
Aujourd'hui, the members of the Union can only lend a helping hand to Greece by going beyond the regulation that prevents them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or in circumstances independent of the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders lend a hand, public opinions and the markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be modified.
Moreover, aid should not only be granted under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by a temporary national budget control by a committee of 'experts' appointed by the European Union.
History shows us that simple promises made by the beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries that will be subject to such measures will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the late Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed its budget over to an expert nominated specifically by the administration of President Barack Obama?
In fact, it would not bother them as much as that.
The expert would not be a Californian by origin, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the Californian state as in that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from which the orders of this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
The Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereign prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those who have a robust emergency aid mechanism must really be accountable.
They must answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they know very well who will foot the bill.
Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany has its part of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not required to account, but which today has adopted an overly excessive monetary policy, thus critically aggravating the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece and Spain).
The enormous current surpluses of Germany further aggravate their situation.
Furthermore, its budgetary stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has benefited significantly from the creation of the euro.
It should give back in kind.
It should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
It should provide more budgetary support.
Isn't it the best placed to exert pressure for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe to a more accomplished political integration.
We can only hope.
